etymologies: mid 17th century: via Latin from Greek palimpsēstos, from palin ‘again’ + psēstos ‘rubbed smooth’

definitions: a manuscript or piece of writing material on which the original writing has been effaced to make room for later writing but of which traces remain.
shortDefinitions: manuscript or piece of writing material on which later writing has been superimposed on effaced earlier writing

definitions: something reused or altered but still bearing visible traces of its earlier form

examples.text: Sutton Place is a palimpsest of the taste of successive owners
